{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Refimprove|date=October 2009}} {{Fascism sidebar|expanded=Related}}
Since the emergence of [[fascism]] in Europe in the first half of the 20th century, the term "fascist" has frequently been used as a [[pejorative]] epithet against a wide range of individuals, political movements, governments, public and private institutions, including those that would not usually be classified as fascist in mainstream political science. It usually serves as an emotionally loaded substitute for [[authoritarian]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}
As early as 1944, British writer [[George Orwell]] commented that following its widespread use in the European press, "the word 'Fascism' is almost entirely meaningless" due to its non-specific use detached from its original political associations.<ref>"It will be seen that, as used, the word 'Fascism' is almost entirely meaningless. In conversation, of course, it is used even more wildly than in print. I have heard it applied to farmers, shopkeepers, Social Credit, corporal punishment, fox-hunting, bull-fighting, the 1922 Committee, the 1941 Committee, Kipling, Gandhi, Chiang Kai-Shek, homosexuality, Priestley's broadcasts, Youth Hostels, astrology, women, dogs and I do not know what else.", [[George Orwell]], [http://orwell.ru/library/articles/As_I_Please/english/efasc What is Fascism?], 1944</ref>
==Soviet Union== The [[Bolshevik]] movement and later the [[Soviet Union]] made frequent use of the "fascist" epithet coming from its conflict with the early German and Italian fascist movements. It was widely used in press and political language to describe either its ideological opponents (such as the [[White movement]]) or even internal fractions of the [[socialism|socialist]] movement (for example, [[social democracy]] which was called [[social fascism]]). Also the [[Nazi]] movement in Germany was described as "fascist" until 1939, when the [[Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact]] was signed, after which [[Nazi–Soviet economic relations (1934–41)|Nazi–Soviet relations]] started to be presented positively in Soviet propaganda.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}
After the [[Operation Barbarossa|Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union]] in 1941, "fascist" was used in the Soviet Union to describe virtually any anti-Soviet activity or opinion. According to [[Marxism–Leninism]], fascism was the "final phase of crisis of bourgeoisie", which "in fascism sought refuge" from "inherent contradictions of capitalism". As a result of this approach, it was almost every Western capitalist country that was "fascist", with the [[Third Reich]] being just the "most reactionary" one.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://militera.lib.ru/h/istoriya_voyny_na_tihom_okeane/16.html | title=Наступление фашизма и задачи Коммунистического Интернационала в борьбе за единство рабочего класса против фашизма | work=7th Comintern Congress | date=20 August 1935 | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://militera.lib.ru/h/12/01/02.html | title=Фашизм – наиболее мрачное порождение империализма | work=История второй мировой войны 1939–1945 гг. | date=1973 | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref> After 1941, "fascist" was used in Soviet Union to describe virtually any anti-Soviet activity: for example, the international investigation on [[Katyn massacre]] was described as "fascist libel"<ref>[[Robert Stiller]], "Semantyka zbrodni"</ref> and the [[Warsaw Uprising]] as "illegal and organised by fascists".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.e-warszawa.com/e-warszawa/1944-powstanie | title=1944 – Powstanie Warszawskie | publisher=e-Warszawa.com | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref> Communist [[Służba Bezpieczeństwa]] described [[Trotskyism]], [[Titoism]] and imperialism as "variants of fascism".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://katalog.bip.ipn.gov.pl/showDetails.do?idx=P&katalogId=2&subpageKatalogId=2&pageNo=1&nameId=18103&osobaId=33354& | title=Dane osoby z katalogu funkcjonariuszy aparatu bezpieczeństwa – Franciszek Przeździał | publisher=Instytut Pamięci Narodowej | date=1951 | accessdate=2015-08-31 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120080346/http://katalog.bip.ipn.gov.pl/showDetails.do?idx=P&katalogId=2&subpageKatalogId=2&pageNo=1&nameId=18103&osobaId=33354& | archivedate=November 20, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>
==Western politics== {{also|Media portrayal of the 2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine}}<!--NOTE: Hatnote templates should only be placed at the TOP of article subsections.--> In the 1980s, the term was used by leftist critics to describe the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]]. The term was later used in the 2000s to describe the administration of [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush]] by its critics and in the late 2010s to describe the candidacy and administration of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]. In her 1970 book ''Beyond Mere Obedience'', radical activist and theologian [[Dorothee Sölle]] coined the term "[[Christofascism|Christofascist]]" to describe [[fundamentalist Christians]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=[[Dorothee Sölle]] |year=1970|title=Beyond Mere Obedience: Reflections on a Christian Ethic for the Future |publisher=Augsburg Publishing House|location=Minneapolis | url=https://books.google.com/?id=zbeCGwAACAAJ&dq}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Confessing Christ in a Post-Christendom Context. |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-66279081.html |quote= ... shall we say this, represent this, live this, without seeming to endorse the kind of christomonism (Dorothee Solle called it "Christofascism"! ... |publisher=The Ecumenical Review |date=July 1, 2000 |accessdate=2007-12-23 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|first=Sarah K. |last=Pinnock |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=The Theology of Dorothee Soelle |url=https://books.google.com/?id=56_VviorwEsC&dq |quote= ... of establishing a dubious moral superiority to justify organized violence on a massive scale, a perversion of Christianity she called Christofascism. ... |isbn=1-56338-404-3 |publisher=Trinity Press International |year=2003 }}</ref>
In 2004, [[Samantha Power]] (lecturer at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]]) reflected Orwell's words from 60 years prior when she stated: "Fascism – unlike communism, socialism, capitalism, or conservatism – is a smear word more often used to brand one's foes than it is a descriptor used to shed light on them".<ref>Power, Samantha. "[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE0DB153AF931A35756C0A9629C8B63 The Original Axis of Evil]", ''[[The New York Times]]'', 2004-05-02.</ref>
In 2006, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] found contrary to the Article 10 (freedom of expression) of [[ECHR]] fining a journalist for calling a right-wing journalist "local neo-fascist", regarding the statement as a value-judgment acceptable in the circumstances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cmiskp.echr.coe.int/tkp197/view.asp?action=html&documentId=811485&portal=hbkm&source=externalbydocnumber&table=F69A27FD8FB86142BF01C1166DEA398649 |title=Case of Karman v. Russia (Application no. 29372/02) Judgment |publisher=European Court of Human Rights |date=March 14, 2007}}</ref>
In 2014, with the outbreak of the [[war in Donbass]] the [[Russian nationalism|Russian nationalists]] and media returned to the "fascist" rhetoric, frequently describing the Ukrainian government after [[Euromaidan]] as "fascist", "Nazi" etc.,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://time.com/3545855/russia-ukraine-war-history/ | title=Russians Re-write History to Slur Ukraine Over War | publisher=Time | date=2014-10-29 | accessdate=2014-10-30 | author=Simon Shuster}}</ref><ref name=NYB140320>{{cite web | url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/mar/20/fascism-russia-and-ukraine/ | title=Fascism, Russia, and Ukraine | work=The New York Review of Books | date=20 March 2014 | accessdate=22 July 2014 | last=Snyder |first= Timothy}}</ref> at the same time accusing them of "Jewish influence" or spreading "gay propaganda".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogs.ft.com/the-world/2014/03/fascism-a-useful-insult/|title = Fascism: a useful insult|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = Financial Times|last = Wagstyl|first = Stefan}}</ref>
In response to multiple authors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/this-is-how-fascism-comes-to-america/2016/05/17/c4e32c58-1c47-11e6-8c7b-6931e66333e7_story.html|title=This is how fascism comes to America|last=Kagan|first=Rober|date=May 18, 2016|website=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post Media|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35050186|title='Racist', 'fascist', 'utterly repellent': What the world said about Donald Trump |last=|first=|date=December 9, 2015|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/going-there-with-donald-trump|title=Going There with Donald Trump |last=Gopnik|first=Adam|date=May 11, 2016|website=The New Yorker|publisher=Condé Nast|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://highlandernews.org/20877/donald-trumps-fascist-tendencies/|title=Donald Trump’s fascist tendencies |last=Swift|first=Nathan|date=October 26, 2015|website=The Highlander|publisher=Highlander Newspaper|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/donald-trump/12041188/Donald-Trump-is-an-outright-fascist-who-should-be-banned-from-Britain-today.html|title=Donald Trump is an outright fascist who should be banned from Britain today |last=Hodges|first=Dan|date=December 9, 2015|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> claiming that the then-Presidential candidate Donald Trump was a "fascist", a 2016 article for [[Vox Media|''Vox'']] cited five historians who study fascism—including [[Roger Griffin]], author of ''The Nature of Fascism''—who stated that Trump does not hold (and is even opposed to) several political viewpoints that are integral to fascism, including viewing violence as an inherent good and an inherent rejection or opposition to a democratic system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2015/12/10/9886152/donald-trump-fascism|title=I asked 5 fascism experts whether Donald Trump is a fascist. Here's what they said.|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=May 19, 2016|website=Vox|publisher=Vox Media|access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>
==Possible explanations for casual uses== {{Quote|text=They employ massive overkill strategy, there are 30, 20 to 30 marshals daily inside the courtroom, it has the atmosphere of an arms camp, the law against us is rigged … and our claims that this law violates our constitutional rights and it’s the same way that we claim that Mayor Daley didn’t have the right to deny us a permit to march or to assemble in the park…. I think it points a direction in the future which is that the government embarked on a course of fascism.|sign=[[Abbie Hoffman]]|source=[[Viking Youth Power Hour]] interview, November, 1969<ref>"[http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/chicago7/hoffmaninterview.html An Interview About the Trial with Abbie Hoffman]"</ref>}}
Several Marxist theories back up particular uses of fascism beyond its usual remit. For instance, [[Nicos Poulantzas|Poulantzas]]'s theory of [[state monopoly capitalism]] could be associated with the idea of a [[military-industrial complex]] to suggest that 1960s America had a fascist social structure, though this kind of [[Maoism|Maoist]] or [[Guevarism|Guevarist]] analysis often underpinned the rhetorical depiction of Cold War authoritarians as fascists.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}
Some Marxist groups – such as the Indian section of the [[Fourth International (post-reunification)|Fourth International]] and the [[Mansoor Hekmat#Views|Hekmatist]] groups in Iran and Iraq – have provided analytical accounts as to why the term "fascist" should be applied to groups such as the [[Hindutva]] movement, the [[Iranian Revolution|1979 Islamic Iranian regime]] or the [[Islamism|Islamist]] sections of the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]]. Other scholars contend that the traditional meaning of the term fascism does not apply to Hindutva groups and may hinder an analysis of their activities.<ref name="Refute">{{cite news |url=http://world.christianpost.com/article/20031219/1016.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113192335/http://world.christianpost.com/article/20031219/1016.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2006 |title=RSS neither Nationalist nor Fascist, Indian Christian priest's research concludes |publisher=[[The Christian Post]] |first=Surojit |last=Chatterjee |date=December 19, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19980823/23550294.html |title=RSS neither nationalist nor fascist, says Christian priest after research |publisher=[[The Indian Express]] |author=P. Venugopal |date=August 23, 1998 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040722005929/http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19980823/23550294.html |archivedate=July 22, 2004 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Walter K. Andersen, Shridhar D. Damle |date=May 1989 | title = The Brotherhood in Saffron: The Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh and Hindu Revivalism | journal = [[American Academy of Political and Social Science#The Annals|Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science]] | volume = 503 | pages = 156–57 | doi = 10.1177/0002716289503001021 }}</ref><ref>''Ethnic and Racial Studies'', Volume 23, Number 3, May 2000, pp. 407–441 [[International Standard Serial Number|ISSN]] 0141-9870 print/ISSN 1466-4356 online.</ref>
