{{redirect|Júma language||Juma language (Carib)}} {{Infobox language |name=Kawahiva |nativename=Kawahib |states=[[Brazil]] |region=[[Mato Grosso]] |ethnicity=(see varieties below) |speakers= {{sigfig|867|2}} |date=2000–2006 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1 = [[Tupian languages|Tupian]] |fam2 = [[Tupí–Guaraní languages|Tupí–Guaraní]] |fam3 = Kawahib |lc1=pah |ld1=[[Tenharim]]–[[Parintintín]] |lc2=urz |ld2=[[Uru-eu-wau-wau]] |lc10=adw |ld10=[[Amondawa]] |lc4=jua |ld4=[[Juma people|Júma]] |lc6=xmo |ld6=Morerebi |lc7=tkf |ld7=? Tukumanféd (unattested) |lc8=wir |ld8=Wiraféd |lc9=paf |ld9=Paranawát |lc3=kuq |ld3=Karipuná (confuses Kawahib with [[Jau-Navo]]) |lc11=api |ld11=[[Apiacá language|Apiacá]] |glotto=tupi1280 |glottorefname=Tupi-Guarani Subgroup VI }}
'''Kawahiva''' (Kawahíb, Kagwahib) is a [[Tupi–Guarani]] [[dialect cluster]] of [[Brazil]]. The major variety is '''Tenharin''' (Tenharin).
The [[Tenharin]], [[Parintintín]], [[Amondawa]], [[Uru-eu-wau-wau]] and [[Juma people|Júma]] peoples, along with a recently contacted group confusingly labeled "[[Nheengatu language|Karipuná]]" in the literature, all call themselves ''Kavahiva''. Their speech is all very similar, and also similar with other languages now extinct. [[Apiaká language|Apiaká]] (incl. Wiraféd) is very similar and may be a dialect.<ref>Hammarström (2015) Ethnologue 16/17/18th editions: a comprehensive review: online appendices</ref>
