* The genitive singular in  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-ī}} is of unknown origin, but is found in both Italic and Celtic. It mostly ousted the older (presumably inherited) genitive in  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-osjo}} in Latin. The older form is found in a few inscriptions, such as  {{lang|la|popliosio valesiosio}} on the [[Lapis Satricanus]]. It is also continued in some pronominal genitives, such as  {{lang|la|cuius}} <  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*kʷojjo-s}} <  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*kʷosjo}}, with  {{lang|itc-x-proto|-s}} added by analogy with the consonant stem genitive in  {{lang|itc-x-proto|-os}}.{{sfn|Sihler|1995|p=387}} In Osco-Umbrian, neither ending survives, being replaced with  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-eis}}, the i-stem ending.
* The nominative plural was originally  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-ōs}} for nouns and adjectives, and  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-oi}} for pronominal forms. The distribution in Proto-Italic is unclear, but both endings certainly still existed. The  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-ōs}} ending was replaced altogether in Latin in favour of  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-oi}}, whence the classical  {{lang|la|-ī}}. In Osco-Umbrian, the reverse happened, where  {{lang|la|*-oi}} was replaced with  {{lang|la|*-ōs}}, whence Oscan  {{lang|osc|-ús}}, Umbrian  {{lang|xum|-us}}.
* In Old Latin, the genitive plural was still generally  {{lang|la|-om}}, later  {{lang|la|-um}}. It was then reformed based on the ā-stem form  {{lang|itc-x-proto|*-āzom}}, giving the classical  {{lang|la|-ōrum}}.

====ā-stems====
This class represents the "first declension" of Latin. It derives primarily from Proto-Indo-European nouns in  {{PIE|*-eh₂-}}, and contained mostly feminine nouns, but maybe a few masculines.

